config.task: Design the system architecture for the OneNote to Joplin Migration Readiness Tool. This is a Tauri v2 desktop app (Rust backend + React 19 frontend) that validates a Windows environment before running onenote-md-exporter. The Rust backend performs 4 system diagnostics: (1) Windows OS version check (10/11), (2) OneNote Win32 v15+ desktop check (not UWP/Store), (3) Word Win32 v15+ desktop check, (4) COM Bridge test-initialization of OneNote.Application and Word.Application objects. The frontend uses React 19, TypeScript 5.8, Vite 7, Tailwind CSS 4, Zustand 5, shadcn/ui, Lucide React. Dark mode only. UI flow: centered 'Run Readiness Scan' button -> diagnostic list (Pass/Fail/Warning) -> evolves into Step-by-Step Wizard on failures -> Download Report (.md) button. Design the Rust command layer (Tauri IPC commands), the React component tree, state management (Zustand store shape), and file structure. Output the architecture as a structured document.

Validate the feasibility of the OneNote to Joplin Migration Readiness Tool concept. Check: (1) Can Rust access Windows Registry for Office version detection? (2) Can Tauri v2 Rust backend initialize COM objects? (3) Is the UWP vs Desktop OneNote detection feasible via registry? (4) What are the known limitations? (5) Is the WSL-to-Windows cross-compile viable for this use case?

Write the implementation plan for the OneNote to Joplin Migration Readiness Tool. Tauri v2 + React 19 desktop app. 4 system checks: Windows OS, OneNote Win32, Word Win32, COM Bridge. Plan covers: scaffolding, Rust backend, React frontend, state management, UI, testing, build pipeline.
Validate the Joplin Desktop installation check feature across Rust backend and React frontend
